### Converting an excel format to a genind object for use in PopGenReport## Make sure your input file is in the correct format.## It must have an ind, pop, lat, long, group and age columns, then 2 columns per microsat locus - 1 column per allele## It must be saved in the .csv format.## Check file format at location /Users/adrianallen/Desktop/Badger IBD vs M. bovis diversity paper/Distance matrices/STR genetic distance#PACKAGESlibrary("PopGenReport")## Then, read in the .csv using the command below.## You must tell the function where each column type is.## If you lack say, ind, pop, long or lat data, enter =NULL## Specify any other columns using the other.min and other.max arguments## The latter tells the function that everything after this range are STR alleles.## Specify that STR data are in format of one allele per columnbadger<-read.genetable("badgergenotypes.csv", ind=1, pop=2, lat=3, long=4, other.min=5, other.max=6, oneColPerAll = TRUE)## You now have a genind object of genotypes to analyse.